@kdheepak you might have more luck making a conda package and using Anaconda's compilers.  There's a blog post at https://www.anaconda.com/blog/developer-blog/utilizing-the-new-compilers-in-anaconda-distribution-5/

There's lots of conda recipe examples out there, too.  Anaconda's are at https://github.com/AnacondaRecipes

There's a recipe that uses swig and the new compilers at https://github.com/AnacondaRecipes/aggregate/blob/master/svn-feedstock/recipe/meta.yaml

@ishtjot It seems like you might be confusing two different things:
- Making a conda environment with a different python version. That’s what https://conda.io/docs/user-guide/getting-started.html#managing-environments is about; you’d do e.g. `conda create -n py3 python=3.5`.
- Building a package of some software that can be installed with conda. That’s what `conda build` does, and it has nothing really to do with creating environments.

